         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="jeru0173.translation" corresp="#jeru0173.transcription">
            <p>Yehud, our father</p>
         </div>
      <div type="edition" subtype="transcription_segmented"><p><w xml:id="jeru0173-1" xml:lang="arc">יהוד</w> <w xml:id="jeru0173-2" xml:lang="arc">אבון</w> </p>
</div>
</body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Ossuary has inner ledge on three sides, red wash, a flat sliding lid, and incised lines picked out in red. Ornamentation consists of two metopes in line frames, each containing a six-petalled rosette within concentric line circles. Inscription is on the chest's back side. יהוד is a contraction of יהודה. אבון is probably the word meaning "father" and not the name Abinah/Abunah. It is attested in Talmudic literature, but during a much later period (200 CE and after) than that of this ossuary. The use of the word not in reference to the three Patriachs constitutes a violation of a ruling in Sem. 1:12, but not an unusual one.</p>
         </div>
